            <path d="M12 0C5.373 0 0 5.373 0 12c0 2.143.566 4.148 1.553 5.887L0 24l6.296-1.529A11.946 11.946 0 0012 24c6.627 0 12-5.373 12-12S18.627 0 12 0zm0 21.818a9.818 9.818 0 01-5.001-1.368l-.36-.213-3.733.906.946-3.643-.234-.374A9.818 9.818 0 1112 21.818z"/>
          </svg>
          Get a Quote
        </a>
        <a href="tel:+94774503744" class="btn-ghost">0774 503 744</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Do -->
  <section class="areas-section">
    <div class="areas-inner">
      <div class="stag reveal">What We Do</div>
      <h2 class="reveal">Three Application Areas</h2>
      <p class="sdesc reveal">
        Each surface has a different exposure profile and failure mode. We apply the
        right system and method for each one.
      </p>
      <div class="area-cards reveal">

        <div class="area-card">
          <div class="ac-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 56 56" fill="none">
              <!-- balcony slab -->
              <rect x="4"  y="34" width="48" height="8"  rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".75"/>
              <!-- posts -->
              <rect x="8"  y="12" width="4"  height="22" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".35"/>
              <rect x="44" y="12" width="4"  height="22" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".35"/>
              <!-- top rail -->
              <rect x="6"  y="10" width="44" height="4"  rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".5"/>
              <!-- water droplets -->
              <path d="M28 18 C28 18 23 23 23 27 a5 5 0 0 0 10 0 C33 23 28 18 28 18Z" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".3"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ac-name">Balcony Waterproofing</div>
          <div class="ac-desc">
            Balconies are one of the most common sources of water ingress into the
            structure below. The slab, upstands, and any wall-floor junctions are all
            treated — with full membrane coverage and correct detailing at drain outlets.
          </div>
          <ul class="ac-list">
            <li>Full slab surface membrane application</li>
            <li>Upstand treatment to correct height</li>
            <li>Drain outlet detailing and collar sealing</li>
            <li>Wall-floor junction reinforcement</li>
            <li>Suitable for tiled or exposed finishes</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://wa.me/94774503744?text=Hello%2C%20I%20would%20like%20a%20balcony%20waterproofing%20quote." class="ac-cta">Quote This →</a>
        </div>

        <div class="area-card">
          <div class="ac-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 56 56" fill="none">
              <!-- flat terrace slab -->
              <rect x="4"  y="36" width="48" height="8"  rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".75"/>
              <!-- parapet walls -->
              <rect x="4"  y="10" width="5"  height="26" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".4"/>
              <rect x="47" y="10" width="5"  height="26" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".4"/>
              <!-- rain lines -->
              <line x1="18" y1="4"  x2="16" y2="14" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="1.5" opacity=".3"/>
              <line x1="28" y1="4"  x2="26" y2="14" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="1.5" opacity=".3"/>
              <line x1="38" y1="4"  x2="36" y2="14" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="1.5" opacity=".3"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ac-name">Terrace Waterproofing</div>
          <div class="ac-desc">
            Terraces carry the full brunt of Sri Lanka's monsoon rainfall. A failed
            terrace membrane means ceiling damage, structural staining, and eventually
            rebar corrosion. The entire deck, parapet bases, and service penetrations
            are fully treated.
          </div>
          <ul class="ac-list">
            <li>Full deck membrane application</li>
            <li>Parapet base and coping junction treatment</li>
            <li>Service pipe and AC penetration sealing</li>
            <li>Expansion joint detailing where required</li>
            <li>Suitable under screed, tiles, or exposed finish</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://wa.me/94774503744?text=Hello%2C%20I%20would%20like%20a%20terrace%20waterproofing%20quote." class="ac-cta">Quote This →</a>
        </div>

        <div class="area-card">
          <div class="ac-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 56 56" fill="none">
              <!-- bathroom box -->
              <rect x="6"  y="6"  width="44" height="44" rx="2" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="2" fill="none" opacity=".55"/>
              <!-- floor area fill -->
              <rect x="8"  y="38" width="40" height="10" rx="0" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".12"/>
              <!-- wall line -->
              <rect x="8"  y="8"  width="5"  height="28" rx="0" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".12"/>
              <rect x="43" y="8"  width="5"  height="28" rx="0" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".12"/>
              <!-- water drop -->
              <path d="M28 16 C28 16 22 22 22 27 a6 6 0 0 0 12 0 C34 22 28 16 28 16Z" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".35"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ac-name">Bathroom Waterproofing</div>
          <div class="ac-desc">
            The most critical step in any bathroom renovation — done before tiling,
            never after. Full floor coverage, walls treated to splash height, and the
            shower recess treated as a wet box with extra membrane layers at corners
            and junctions.
          </div>
          <ul class="ac-list">
            <li>Full floor membrane — no gaps, no shortcuts</li>
            <li>Walls treated to splash height (minimum 1.8m in shower)</li>
            <li>Corner and junction reinforcement tape</li>
            <li>Shower recess double-coat treatment</li>
            <li>Drain collar sealing and outlet detailing</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://wa.me/94774503744?text=Hello%2C%20I%20would%20like%20a%20bathroom%20waterproofing%20quote." class="ac-cta">Quote This →</a>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Use -->
  <section class="product-section">
    <div class="product-inner">
      <div class="product-text reveal">
        <div class="stag">What We Use</div>
        <h2>Tokyo Super 2K</h2>
        <p class="sdesc">
          A two-component polymer-modified cementitious waterproofing membrane —
          the correct product for concrete and masonry substrates in Sri Lanka's
          climate.
        </p>
        <div class="product-specs">
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Type</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Two-component (2K) cementitious membrane</span>
          </div>
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Application</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Brush or roller — applied in minimum two coats</span>
          </div>
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Substrate</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Concrete, masonry, render, and screed</span>
          </div>
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Flexibility</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Accommodates minor structural movement — crack-bridging</span>
          </div>
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Tile-ready</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Fully tile-bondable surface after cure — no primer required</span>
          </div>
          <div class="spec-row">
            <span class="spec-label">Curing</span>
            <span class="spec-val">Full cure before tiling or screed application — never rushed</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="product-visual reveal">
        <div class="pv-card">
          <div class="pv-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 80 80" fill="none">
              <!-- bucket / container shape -->
              <path d="M20 28 L16 68 L64 68 L60 28 Z" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="2" fill="none" opacity=".5"/>
              <rect x="16" y="20" width="48" height="10" rx="2" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="2" fill="none" opacity=".6"/>
              <!-- label area -->
              <rect x="24" y="36" width="32" height="22" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".08" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="1" opacity=".25"/>
              <rect x="28" y="40" width="24" height="2" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".3"/>
              <rect x="28" y="46" width="18" height="2" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".2"/>
              <rect x="28" y="52" width="21" height="2" rx="1" fill="#c4784a" opacity=".2"/>
              <!-- handle -->
              <path d="M28 20 C28 12 52 12 52 20" stroke="#c4784a" stroke-width="2" fill="none" opacity=".4"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <div class="pv-name">Tokyo Super 2K</div>
          <div class="pv-sub">Two-Component Waterproofing Membrane</div>
          <div class="pv-badges">
            <span>Cementitious</span>
            <span>Crack-Bridging</span>
            <span>Tile-Bondable</span>
            <span>2-Coat System</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="why-note">
          <div class="wn-label">Why 2K over single-component?</div>
          <p>
            Two-component systems activate a polymer reaction when mixed — producing
            a stronger, more flexible, and more durable membrane than standard
            single-component coatings. For exposed terraces and wet areas that will
            be tiled, 2K is the correct specification.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Process -->
  <section class="process-section">
    <div class="process-inner">
      <div class="stag">How It Works</div>
      <h2>Our Waterproofing Process</h2>
      <p class="sdesc">
        Waterproofing done right is a methodical process — preparation is as important
        as the membrane itself.
      </p>
      <div class="steps">
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">01</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">Site Assessment</div>
            <div class="step-desc">We inspect the surface condition, check for existing cracks, identify high-risk junctions (corners, drains, penetrations), and confirm the correct scope.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">02</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">Surface Preparation</div>
            <div class="step-desc">Surface cleaned, loose material removed, cracks cut out and filled, and any high spots ground back. The membrane is only as good as what it bonds to.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">03</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">Junction & Detail Work</div>
            <div class="step-desc">Reinforcement tape applied at all corners, wall-floor junctions, and drain collars before membrane — the areas that fail first if not detailed correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">04</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">First Coat — Tokyo Super 2K</div>
            <div class="step-desc">Components mixed to correct ratio, first coat applied by brush or roller to full coverage. Coat thickness checked. Left to cure to touch-dry before second coat.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">05</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">Second Coat</div>
            <div class="step-desc">Second coat applied perpendicular to the first — cross-coat method ensures no pinholes or thin spots. Upstands and high-risk areas receive additional coverage.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step reveal">
          <div class="step-num">06</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <div class="step-name">Cure & Handover</div>
            <div class="step-desc">Membrane allowed to fully cure — no tiling or screed applied over it until it is ready. We confirm cure status before handing over for the next trade.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-inner">
      <div class="stag">Common Questions</div>
      <h2>Waterproofing FAQ</h2>
      <div class="faqs">
        <div class="faq reveal">
          <div class="faq-q">When should waterproofing be done — before or after tiling?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Always before tiling. The membrane is applied to the bare substrate — concrete, screed, or masonry — and must be fully cured before tiles are laid over it. Applying waterproofing over or behind tiles defeats the purpose entirely.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq reveal">
          <div class="faq-q">Why Tokyo Super 2K and not a standard coating?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Two-component systems are stronger and more flexible than single-component coatings. The polymer activation gives better crack-bridging, better adhesion, and a tile-bondable surface — which matters when the membrane will be tiled over. For balconies and bathrooms in Sri Lanka's climate, this is the correct specification.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq reveal">
          <div class="faq-q">Do you waterproof as a standalone service or only as part of a renovation?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Both. We waterproof as a standalone service — for example, a leaking balcony or terrace that just needs the membrane reapplied — as well as as part of a full bathroom renovation or new construction.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq reveal">
          <div class="faq-q">How long does waterproofing take to cure before we can tile?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Tokyo Super 2K is typically ready for tiling within 24–48 hours depending on temperature and humidity. We confirm readiness on site before handing over — we never rush this stage.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq reveal">
          <div class="faq-q">Is waterproofing included in the bathroom renovation price?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — bathroom waterproofing is fully included in the <a href="/services/bathroom-renovation">Bathroom Renovation</a> rate. For standalone balcony and terrace waterproofing, we quote separately after a site visit.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTA />
  <Footer />
</Layout>

